{
  "doc_id": "54407",
  "text": "The surface-related origin of the SAL known to explain the YB of GaN not only agrees with many studies linking this YB to the surface [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] but also allows for the prediction that if holes are brought near the surface in n-GaN devices, surface electroluminescence (SEL) proportional to the surface charge will be observed. Let us show that this SEL is very likely the weak EL found recently in the FET devices of [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] , where it has been attributed to hot-electron effects. Using our model for Device no. 1 at the surface, we do not need hot-electron effects at all, in agreement with recent studies discarding these types of effects in the electrical degradation of GaN FETs [CITATION_8] . Our model also predicts that this SEL will track the dynamics of the surface charge in n-GaN devices and that this SEL will not be a yellow peak but a \"redder\" luminescence.",
